{[%evp 0,40,18,24,13,4,17,17,17,-16,9,7,5,5,12,-6,0,20,39,39,31,47,39,31,45,39,
45,15,41,33,32,24,46,0,31,5,5,18,16,16,19,19,19]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 Bb7 {Recently, this
continuation has been getting popular at the highest level. Even
Nepomniachtchi prepared this line for the World Championship match against
Carlsen. Had Magnus played 8.a4 instead of 8.Ne5, 8...Bb7 would surely have
happened. The fact that Nepo played 8...Bb7 against Giri at the World Rapid
Championship in Warsaw only confirms my hypothesis. I decided to make this
move the cornerstone of the current repertoire. There are 3 points that
justify this choice: 1) Since few games have been played, there is no
theoretical overload 2) The best engines have proven the correctness of
Black's concept 3) The arising positions are not difficult to handle from a
human perspective.} ({Until recently, the move 7...b5 was always played in
connection with} 8... b4 {Nevertheless, the top-level practice has shown that
after the sequence} 9. Nfd2 c6 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. Be3 Qh5 13. Nbd2 {
Black cannot solve all the problems.}) {The point of Black's last move becomes
clear after} 9. axb5 a6 {Black is sacrificing a pawn for development and piece
activity. Conceptually, this line is pretty similar to the Benko Gambit.
Meanwhile, with the early ...Bb7, Black neutralizes White's main weapon in the
Catalan - the g2-bishop.} 10. Nc3 {White keeps developing his pieces instead
of speeding up Black's development with 10.bxa6. The drawback of this approach
is that the knight is going to be vulnerable on b5. Therefore, White should
waste a tempo by retreating it to c3. The main crossroads is being reached
after} ({The main move} 10. bxa6 {is dealt with in the next chapter.}) 10...
axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5 Bd5 {After defending the c4-pawn, Black is ready
to follow up with the thematic ...c7-c5. After the eventual dxc5, the arising
symmetrical structure is usually good for Black. Even though the c4-pawn might
be slightly vulnerable, it provides a lot of space on the queenside. At the
same time, White's b2-pawn can also be put under pressure. Another idea that
we should keep in mind (after the retreat Nc3) is ...Bxf3 followed by ...Qxd4.}
13. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Ge2e4] This is White's main move. He wants to either
obtain a bishop pair by means of Nxd5 or expand in the centre with e2-e4.} ({
Another tricky attempt is} 13. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Ge7f6,Ge2e4] Very often,
White's dark-squared bishop is useless in Catalan positions. Therefore, the
idea of the last move is Bxf6 followed by e2-e4. Black should handle the
arising positions with care. The best reaction seems to be} Na6 $1 {[%cal
Gc7c5] preparing ...c7-c5.} ({The immediate} 13... c5 $6 {runs into} 14. dxc5 {
when Black is forced to recapture with the bishop.} Bxc5 15. Nc3 {The only
game featuring this position saw} h6 $6 ({Better would have been} 15... Nbd7
16. Nxd5 exd5 17. b3 cxb3 18. Qxb3 Qb6 19. Qxb6 Bxb6 20. Bh3 $14 {with a
slight advantage for White.}) 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Nd2 $1 $16 {White is better
due to the weak c4-pawn. He managed to convert the advantage in the game 1-0  
(36)Sargsyan,S (2626) -Harutyunian,T (2564) Tashkent 2021}) 14. Bxf6 ({The
alternative} 14. Ra1 {is well met by} Nb4 15. Qd2 c5 {The logical sequence} 16.
Bxf6 gxf6 17. dxc5 Bxc5 18. Nc3 Bxf3 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 20. Bxf3 f5 $11 {results in
a completely drawn endgame.}) 14... Bxf6 15. e4 {The most principled
continuation.} ({I have also examined} 15. Qa4 {when White must react with} Qd7
$1 {the point being} 16. Qxa6 (16. Ra1 Rb8 17. Nc3 Qxa4 18. Nxa4 Bxf3 19. Bxf3
Bxd4 $15) 16... Ra8 17. Na7 c5 {It turns out that the pin along the a-file is
very annoying. In order not to find himself in trouble, White should liquidate
into a drawn endgame -} 18. Ra1 cxd4 19. Ne1 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 d3 21. exd3 Bxb2 22.
Ra5 Bc3 23. Rc5 Bxe1 24. Qxc4 Bb4 $11 {with a draw.}) ({As usual,} 15. Nc3 {
is well met by} Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Qxd4 $11) 15... Bc6 16. Na3 {If White manages to
comfortably take the c4-pawn with a knight, he would enjoy a slight but stable
advantage. Therefore, Black should play energetically.} ({Harmless is} 16. Qxc4
Bxe4 17. Nc3 Bb7 $11 {with an immediate equality.}) 16... Qa8 $1 17. Re1 c3 $1
{This elegant tactical resource allows Black to solve all problems.} 18. bxc3
Nc5 19. Nb1 Nxe4 20. Ne5 Bxe5 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Qxe4 Qxe4 23. Rxe4 Bf6 $11 {
The position is equal.}) ({The attempt to increase the pressure on c4 by means
of} 13. Na3 {does not work optimally because of the vulnerable d4-pawn. After}
Nc6 14. Nxc4 {Black's simplest solution would be} Bxf3 ({Of course, there is
nothing wrong with} 14... Qa8 15. Be3 Nb4 16. Qc1 Na2 17. Qc2 Nb4 18. Qc1 Na2
19. Qc2 Nb4 {with a repetition. 1/2-1/2 (19) Ftacnik,L (2510)-Nayhebaver,M  
(2485) Tornelo INT 2021}) 15. Bxf3 Nxd4 16. Qd3 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Qd4 $11 {
The game should be a draw.}) ({Completely harmless is} 13. Bf4 c5 14. dxc5 Qa5
15. Nc3 Qxc5 $11 {with full equality.}) 13... Bxf3 $1 14. Bxf3 Qxd4 15. Be3 {
So far, this position has been reached in 3 games. All of them continued with
15...Qe5. In my opinion, however, slightly more precise is} Qd6 $5 {[%cal
Gd6a6,Gd6b4] keeping the options of ...Qb4 or ...Qa6 if needed. Additionally, .
..Nc6 becomes an option. Black has no intention of keeping the extra pawn.
Nevertheless, in order to take it back, White needs to invest time. Meanwhile,
Black will either simplify the position even further or exchange one of the
white bishops.} 16. Ra1 ({Another attempt is to play against the c4-pawn by
means of} 16. Rc1 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gc3b5,Gc2c4] Black equalizes by making natural
moves -} Nbd7 17. Ne4 ({In case of} 17. Nb5 {Black should follow with} Qb4 18.
Qxc4 Qxc4 19. Rxc4 Rb8 20. Nxc7 Rxb2 $11 {with equality.}) 17... Qb4 18. Qxc4
Qxc4 19. Rxc4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Bd6 $11 {Black enjoys comfortable equality.}) ({
After} 16. Rd1 {I would prefer} Qa6 {[%cal Gb8c6] From the a6-square, besides
protecting the c4-pawn, the queen supports the move ...Nc6 as well.} 17. Ne4
Nc6 $11 {Black has at least an equal position since White needs to invest
additional time to regain the c4-pawn.}) 16... Nc6 17. Ne4 ({Of course,} 17.
Rd1 {is met by} Nb4 {when after} 18. Qa4 Nfd5 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Bd4 c5 21. Bc3
Nxc3 22. bxc3 Qe5 23. Qxc4 Bf6 $11 {Black has a comfortable equality.}) 17...
Nd4 $1 {This intermediate move is the point behind 16...Nc6.} 18. Qxc4 Nxf3+
19. exf3 Nxe4 20. fxe4 h6 $11 {The position is completely equal. As usual,
both sides have one weak pawn on the queenside. These weaknesses balance each
other out.} *

