this endgame against your computer. In this way, you will face no problems
when a similar position arises in a practical game. Below, I show how to react
against White's most straightforward winning attempt -} 26. Rc7 Kf8 27. d5 {
This advance is White's only constructive idea. He is trying to put pressure
on Black's most vulnerable spot - the f7-pawn.} exd5 28. Bxd5 Be7 29. Kg2 Rb5
30. Bf3 h5 $11 {Black can just keep waiting in this position. The draw is
obvious.}) 21. Qf4 h6 22. h4 Be4 $1 {Transposes to 19...h6} ({Nepomniachtchi
played} 22... Bf6 {when after} 23. e3 $14 {White got a slight edge.
Nevertheless, Black made a draw rather convincingly.½-½ (43) Giri, A (2772)
-Nepomniachtchi,I (2782) Warsaw 2021})) 20. h4 {This thematic move is designed
to secure the f4-square for the queen.} ({The setup with Qf4 without h2-h4
does not work tactically. Here is an illustrative line -} 20. Rd1 cxd4 21. cxd4
Rd8 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7f6,Ga8a4,Gd5f3]} 22. Qf4 g5 $1 {This is one of the key
points behind ...h7-h6!} 23. Qc7 Qa4 24. Rd2 Rd7 25. Qc2 Qxc2 26. Rxc2 Bxf3 27.
Bxf3 Rxd4 $11 {with a draw.}) ({Another typical idea for White is to exchange
the light-squared bishops by means of} 20. Ne1 {Black's most logical reaction
seems to be} Bxg2 {when the following endgame is likely to arise:} 21. Nxg2 Rd8
22. dxc5 ({In the event of} 22. Rd1 $6 {Black is going to follow with} Bf6 $11
{[%cal Gc5d4,Gc3d4,Ga8a4] The d4-pawn will be lost since ...Qa4 is coming.})
22... Qc6 23. Ne1 Bxc5 24. Qf3 Rc8 25. Qxc6 Rxc6 26. Nd3 Ba3 $11 {The draw is
obvious since the c3-pawn is doomed.}) 20... cxd4 21. cxd4 Rd8 22. Qf4 {
Transposes to Giri,A - Nepomniachtchi,I, 2021} Be4 $1 {This is my improvement.
Now, White cannot reach his optimal setup. For example, after} 23. e3 Bd6 24.
Qg4 Bf5 25. Qh5 Qa2 $44 {[%cal Gd8b8,Gf5d3] Black has tremendous compensation
for the pawn. He will proceed with ...Bd3 followed by ...Rb8.} *

