{[%evp 0,34,18,24,30,17,17,4,17,-7,5,5,3,9,3,-12,31,-4,28,30,18,6,-1,19,7,8,30,
7,2,-3,10,17,32,15,15,4,20]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O
6. O-O dxc4 7. Qa4 b6 8. Qxc4 {This is the positional continuation. White is
playing for a very tiny edge in a symmetrical position. You can often see this
line even at the highest level. The main reason for its popularity is the
risk-free character of the game.} Bb7 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black is ready to follow
with ...c7-c5 on the next move. White's main continuation is} 9. Nc3 ({The
natural} 9. Rd1 {is not independent since after} c5 10. Nc3 {we transpose to
the main line.}) ({In my opinion, the move} 9. Bf4 {is a bit premature since
it's still not clear which is the best position for the bishop. Therefore,
White should be as flexible as possible. In this position, Black's best option
is the immediate} c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 Qc8 $1 {[%csl Rc4] Remember this
thematic move. First of all, by creating an opposition along the c-file, Black
is winning an important tempo due to the threat of ...Bxf2. At the same time,
after the eventual exchange of the light-squared bishops, the black queen will
occupy the comfortable b7-square.} 12. Qb3 Nbd7 13. Rac1 a5 {[%cal Gb7c6,Gc8b7]
With his last move, Black gains space on the queenside and secures the
position of the dark-squared bishop. Later on, he can proceed with ...Bc6
followed by ...Qb7. A possible continuation would be} 14. Ne1 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 Qb7
$11 {Black is completely fine in this position. Only White can experience
slight practical problems due to his vulnerable king.}) ({After} 9. Bg5 Nbd7
10. Nc3 c5 11. Rfd1 Rc8 {once again, we transpose to the main line.}) 9... c5 {
The most straightforward approach. Sooner or later, the central tension will
be released. In the arising symmetrical structure, White will enjoy slightly
superior piece activity. Nevertheless, armed with powerful engines, we know
exactly how to neutralize White's symbolic initiative.} 10. Rd1 {This is the
