{[%evp 0,21,18,24,30,17,17,17,17,5,3,3,23,11,11,-16,-24,-17,-19,-63,-61,-27,
-37,-12]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Na3
{This interesting move was recently tried by Magnus Carlsen. If allowed, White
wants to comfortably take the c4-pawn with the knight. In such a case, he will
get a considerable advantage since Black cannot develop his queenside.
Therefore, the most logical follow-up will be} Bxa3 8. bxa3 {We have reached a
typical Catalan structure. From a practical perspective, the position is
playable for both sides due to the imbalances created by the move 7...Bxa3.
White wants to put pressure along the b-file, thus increasing the influence of
his Catalan bishop. The dark-squared bishop can join the game via a3 after the
advance a3-a4. On the other hand, Black has a better pawn structure and
superiority on the light squares. Additionally, White should invest some time
to regain the pawn. Black's most reliable option seems to be} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]
In the Catalan, the development of the light-squared bishop is Black's first
priority. The next move will be ...Bc6. Since White has exchanged his
queenside knight, he does not have good control of the central squares e4 and
d5. Hence, it will be very difficult to restrict the black bishop by means of
the thematic e2-e4. A very logical alternative to the main line with 9.Ne5 is}
9. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] White's priority is to activate his problematic
dark-squared bishop via a3. This move was recently tried by the World Champion
Magnus Carlsen in his game against Anish Giri.} ({Even though} 9. Qc2 {is
statistically less popular, many strong players gave it a shot. Before
anything else, White wants to regain the pawn. Later on, he will rely on his
bishop pair and space advantage,} Bc6 10. Qxc4 {Delaying this natural capture
is not a good option.} ({The move} 10. Re1 {was seen in the game 0-1 (27) Muha,
M (2323)-Drnovsek,G (2384) Split 2019. White prepares e2-e4 but gives Black
the chance to protect the c4-pawn with} b5 $1 {With the bishop being already
on c6, this advance works quite well.} 11. e4 Nbd7 12. Bf4 a6 {[%cal Gd8c8]}
13. a4 Qc8 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7] White's central domination cannot fully
compensate for the missing pawn. Besides being a protected passer, the c4-pawn
provides a lot of space on the queenside.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qc2 {[%cal Gf1e1,
Ge2e4] By keeping the control of the e4-square, White hopes to execute the
idea Re1 followed by e2-e4.} ({Black does not have any problems after} 11. Qc3
{when Black has at least two good options. A natural follow-up is} Nbd7 {
[%cal Ga8c8,Gc7c5] preparing ...Rc8 followed by ...c7-c5.} ({Another thematic
idea for this pawn structure would be} 11... Nc6 12. Rd1 Be4 {[%cal Gd8d5]
This idea was seen in the game ½-½ (27) Smirin, I (2555)-Rozentalis, E (2565)
Leningrad 1990. Black applies his light-square strategy. The next moves will
be ...Qd5 followed by ...Rad8. By putting pressure on d4, Black wants to
provoke e2-e3, further weakening the light squares.}) 12. a4 Re8 13. a5 b6 14.
Rd1 Rc8 15. Bf1 c5 $11 {Black enjoyed comfortable equality in ½-½ (56)
Johansen,A (2356)-Suto,J (2355) ICCF email 2020}) ({In the event of} 11. Qd3 {
Black can again apply his light square strategy with} Be4 12. Qe3 Qd5 {[%cal
Gb8c6] Remember that this setup works almost always when Black managed to
exchange his dark-squared bishop for a knight.} 13. Bb2 {This position
occurred in 1-0 (38) Kett,T (2223)-Bullen,A (2098) Bridgend 2018. At this
point, Black could have played} Qb5 {forcing the bishop to the vulnerable
c3-square before proceeding with ...Nc6.} ({Quite obviously, there is nothing
wrong with the immediate} 13... Nc6 {[%cal Gf8d8]}) 14. Bc3 Nc6 $132 {Black
enjoys his typical play on the light squares. Having a bishop on c3, White
should always reckon with ...Nd5.}) 11... Nbd7 {Since the white queen is on
the c-file, it makes sense to prepare ...Rc8 followed by ...c7-c5.} ({As you
already know, my other favourite approach is the light-square strategy
introduced by} 11... Be4 {[%cal Gb8c6] followed by ...Nc6.}) 12. Re1 {[%cal
Ge2e4] White should immediately start preparing e2-e4.} ({After the pointless} 
12. Bf4 $6 {Black can follow with} Rc8 13. Rfc1 c5 $15 {This position occurred
in the game ½-½ (23) Terreu Serra,F-Marin,I (2261) Hospitalet 1994. Black's
position is already preferable due to his better pawn structure and White's
misplaced queen.}) 12... Be4 13. Qb2 h6 {[%csl Rc1,Gg5][%cal Gc7c5] I like
this move a lot. Since White's dark-squared bishop is often useless in this
structure, it makes sense to prevent Bg5.} 14. Bd2 c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Rac1 b6
$11 {The position is equal.}) ({A strong grandmaster played} 9. Bb2 $2 {
when after} Bc6 10. Qc2 b5 $19 {Black was basically winning since White does
not have any compensation for the pawn. This position occurred in the game 0-1
(67) Cordova,E (2592)-Elgersma,O (2298) Chess.com INT 2020}) ({Getting rid of
the dark-squared bishop by means of} 9. Bg5 Bc6 10. Bxf6 {is another logical
option. Nevertheless, this is not a play for an advantage.} ({But not} 10. Rc1
$2 b5 11. Re1 Be4 $19 {when Black had a winning advantage in the game 1-0 (39)
Adrian, C-Jasinczuk, J Clermont Ferrand 1985}) 10... Qxf6 11. Qc2 Nd7 {This
natural developing move is more than enough for equality.} ({Another possible
line is} 11... b5 12. a4 a6 13. axb5 axb5 14. a4 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 c6 $11 {when
White still needs to demonstrate how he is going to restore the material
balance. Of course, the position is objectively equal.}) 12. Qxc4 Rfd8 13. Rfd1
Qe7 14. Qd3 Nf6 $11 {Black enjoyed pleasant equality in the game ½-½ (29)
Murey, J (2475)-Geller, E (2545) Moscow 1982.}) ({The most popular move} 9. Ne5
{is covered in the next chapter.}) 9... Bc6 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Qc2 {Only after
developing the dark-squared bishop, White is going after the pawn.} ({In case
of} 11. Rc1 {Black will keep the pawn with} Bd5 {A very typical idea to
remember is that} 12. Ne5 {is best met by} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] As
mentioned earlier, the move Ne5 often makes the d4-pawn vulnerable. The game
might continue} 14. Nxc6 Qd5+ 15. Kg1 Qxc6 16. Qc2 {This position occurred in
0-1 (82) Kutynec,V (2310)-Lugovskoy,M (2432) Pardubice 2015. At this point,
the simplest would have been} e5 ({A more fighting approach is} 16... Rad8 17.
Qxc4 Qe4 $11 {when Black will be trying to use the power of the tandem Queen &
Knight. Such a strategy is justified by the vulnerable light squares around
the white king.}) 17. dxe5 Rxe5 18. Qxc4 Qxc4 19. Rxc4 Rxe2 20. Rxc7 Rxa2 $11 {
The draw is obvious.}) 11... Nbd7 12. Rac1 ({The immediate} 12. Qxc4 {can be
