17. Rxc7 Nc4 18. Bb4 Rec8 19. Rxc8+ Rxc8 $15 {Black is better. He enjoys firm
control of the light-squares and a powerful queenside majority.}) {This
position was reached in the game Carlsen, M - Giri, A, Tata Steel, 2022. In my
opinion, Black should have played} 12... Bd5 {and answer} 13. Rfe1 {with} a5 {
[%csl Ra4] Fixing the a4-pawn is an important part of Black's strategy. It
turns out that now, the advance e2-e4 is not that profitable for White.
Probably, White should play} 14. Red1 {[%cal Gf3e5] with the idea of Ne5.} ({
After the tempting} 14. e4 $6 Bc6 15. Qxc4 {Black can play} Bxe4 16. Qxc7 Bc6
17. Qxd8 Rexd8 $15 {In this position, the better pawn structure is far more
important than White's bishop pair. Black is already better.}) 14... Be4 {
This is the simplest. Black immediately goes for his usual light square
strategy.} ({An interesting alternative is} 14... Qc8 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7
$132 {which also seems to work fine. Nevertheless, I don't want to give White
