{[%evp 0,22,18,23,23,17,17,17,17,-1,1,1,11,11,11,-45,-32,-56,-46,-26,-31,-47,
-13,-52,-88]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7.
Nbd2 {White wants to comfortably take the c4-pawn with the knight. If he
manages to do so, he will enjoy a typical Catalan pressure. The drawback of
this move is that the knight closes the way of the queen and hinders the
development of the c1-bishop. Additionally, the d4-pawn is now vulnerable.} b5
{This move is the reason why 7.Nbd2 does not work well. This move usually
works very well against the setups based on Nbd2. The explanation is simple.
In such structures, White's most effective way of putting pressure is the
construction Nc3 and a4. Obviously, the d2-knight cannot put pressure on b5.
Additionally, with the knight being on b1, White often undermines Black's
queenside structure with b2-b3. When the knight is already committed to d2,
the move b2-b3 is well met by ...c4-c3 followed by ...b5-b4.} 8. a4 {Sooner or
later, White has to play this move.} ({The line} 8. Ne5 Nd5 9. a4 c6 {
transposes to 8.a4.}) 8... c6 9. Qc2 {[%cal Gb2b3] White prepares the thematic
b2-b3 but exposes the queen. Quite obviously, the immediate b2-b3 can be met
by ...c4-c3.} ({The main alternative is} 9. Ne5 {Quite typically, Black
answers with} Nd5 {when it's not clear how White is going to increase his
pressure.} 10. e4 {This is the most aggressive continuation. Nevertheless,
it's important to point out that this move has at least three serious
drawbacks: 1) closing the g2-bishop 2) making the d4-pawn vulnerable 3)
weakening the d3-square} ({As we know,} 10. b3 $2 {does not work in view of} c3
11. Ne4 b4 $19 {when Black already had a winning position in the game 0-1 (27)
Azadaliyev, J (2088)-Andreikin, D (2724) Chess.com INT 2021}) ({The exchange} 
10. axb5 $2 cxb5 {only helps Black. Besides enjoying a terrific pawn structure,
he is ready to oppose the Catalan bishop by means of ...Bb7. Additionally,
White cannot put any pressure on the black queenside. The following examples
proved this evaluation.} 11. Ne4 ({After} 11. Qc2 Bb7 12. e4 Nb4 13. Qc3 N8c6
$19 {Black was basically winning in the game 0-1 (43) Cooper, A (1904)-Tristan,
L (2535) Chess.com INT 2020. Besides being a healthy pawn up, he has a big
positional advantage as well.}) ({The move} 11. e4 {is even worse now.} Nb4 {
[%cal Gc8b7,Gb8c6] Black is ready to proceed with ...Bb7 followed by ...N8c6,
thus putting tremendous pressure on d4.} 12. Ndf3 ({Typically, after} 12. d5
exd5 13. exd5 Bb7 {the d5-pawn is quite vulnerable. The tactical trick} 14. d6
{backfires after} Bxg2 15. dxe7 Qxe7 $19 {[%csl Re5] since the e5-knight is
hanging. 0-1 (41) Telke, H (2092) -Biehler, T (2213) Germany 2018}) 12... Bb7
13. Ne1 N8c6 $19 {0-1 (23) Longo, E-Geller,E (2525) Bad Woerishofen 1991}) ({
It's not a surpise that after} 11. b3 $2 c3 {White is on the verge of the
defeat.} 12. Ndc4 a5 13. e4 Nf6 14. Ne3 {This position occurred in the game
½-½ (46) Polgar, I (2435)-Horvath, Z (2350) Hungary 1992. Now, after the
simple} Bb7 15. Qd3 b4 $19 {Black's queenside pawn constellation would have
given him a winning advantage.}) 11... Bb7 12. Bd2 ({Nothing changes} 12. Nc3 {
1-0 (30) Hovyan,N (1505)-Zhang,J (1244) Batumi 2016 Now, the simplest would
have been} Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qd5+ 15. f3 a5 $19 {when Black is
winning. The queenside pawns are unstoppable.}) ({Of course, after} 12. b3 c3
13. Qd3 b4 $19 {the c3-pawn gives Black a winning advantage. 0-1 (25) Lucena,L
(2193)-Pazos Gambarrotti,P (2393) Havana 2003}) 12... Nc6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 $19 {
This position was reached in the game 0-1 (36) Golubenko,V (2209)-Liang,J  
(2340) Chess.com INT 2020. Black has a decisive advantage since White has no
compensation for the pawn.}) ({Pointless is} 10. Ne4 {which occurred in the
game 1-0 (39) Pantev,V (2414)-Karas,M (2267) Chess. com INT 2017. Black has
enough time to organize his queenside play -} f6 11. Nf3 a5 12. Bd2 Nd7 $17 {
[%cal Gc8b7,Gf6f5] White does not have any compensation for the pawn. Black
can already consider expanding further by means of ...Bb7 followed by ...f6-f5.
}) 10... Nb4 11. d5 {The only way of justifying the advance e2-e4. This
position occurred in the game 0-1 (52) Troyke,C (2317)-Munkhzul,T (2278) Chess.
com INT 2020. In fact, White does not have any threats. Therefore, Black can
just play} a6 {strengthening the queenside structure.} 12. Nxc6 ({After} 12.
dxc6 $2 {[%cal Ga4b5,Ga1a8] with the threat of axb5, Black should start with}
Qc7 {and only after} 13. Ndf3 {play} N8xc6 14. Nxc6 Qxc6 $19 {with completely
winning position.}) 12... N8xc6 13. dxc6 Rb8 14. axb5 axb5 $17) (9. axb5 $2
cxb5 10. Ne5 Nd5 {transposes to 9. Ne5.}) ({We already know that with a knight
on d2, the advance} 9. e4 {is not particularly threatening. Black can play
virtually everything. A sensible option would be} Na6 {planning to occupy the
weakened b4-square.} ({The alternative} 9... a5 10. e5 Nd5 11. Ne4 Nd7 $17 {
makes sense as well.}) 10. e5 Nd5 11. Ne4 Nab4 12. Bd2 a5 $17 {This position
occurred in the game 0-1 (58) Granados Gomez,M (2425)-Comas Fabrego,L (2509)
Barcelona 2004. Black's fantastic knights and strong pawn structure prevent
White from creating any activity.}) 9... Na6 {In my opinion, this is the most
precise continuation. Black immediately wants to make use of the vulnerable
white queen by means of . ..Nb4.} 10. b3 {Otherwise, it's impossible to
justify the move 9.Qc2.} ({For example, in the event of} 10. Rd1 $6 {which was
seen in the game 1-0 (42) Kesik, K (2243)-Jaeger, D (2164) Germany 2013, Black
would just follow with} Nb4 11. Qb1 a5 $17 {with a huge advantage. White has
no counterplay.}) ({Black will gladly welcome the exchanges that arise after} 
10. Ne4 $6 Nb4 11. Qb1 ({The attempt to activate the queen by means of} 11.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Qe4 {was seen in the game 0-1 (27) Figura,A (1949)-Morcin,T  
(2117) LSS email 2012. At this point, the most natural follow-up would have
been} Nd5 13. Bd2 a5 $17 {[%cal Ga8a7] with a healthy extra pawn. Remember
that after ...a7-a5, Black often brings his rook into the game via the 7th
rank.}) 11... Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nd5 13. Rd1 a5 {Once again, we see the same
concept.} 14. h4 Bd6 15. Bd2 Qc7 $17 {This position occurred in the game 0-1  
(46) Goy, U (1987)-Warzecha, H (1979) GER email 2012 White does not have any
compensation for the pawn.}) 10... Nb4 11. Qb2 Ba6 {Another precise move. It's
important to keep the c4-pawn as long as possible.} ({After} 11... cxb3 $6 12.
Nxb3 $44 {White achieves exactly what he wants. In this typical position with
a backward pawn on c6, he has more than enough compensation.}) 12. axb5 ({
Trying to provoke ...cxb3 with} 12. Ne5 $2 {does not work tactically. Black has
} Nfd5 $1 {at his disposal. The idea is to give the pawn back in order to
enjoy superior piece activity. A typical example of a transformation of
advantages.} 13. bxc4 ({After} 13. Ne4 $2 cxb3 {White is collapsing.} 14. a5 ({
the problem is that after} 14. Qxb3 bxa4 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ga6e2] the e2-pawn
is hanging.}) 14... f6 15. Nf3 Nc2 16. Rb1 Qxa5 $19 {Black was already winning
in the game 0-1 (24) Pedersen, E (2415) -Muir, A (2290) Aarhus 1990}) 13...
bxc4 14. Nexc4 ({The alternative} 14. Ndxc4 $2 {is dropping a piece after} f6
$19) 14... c5 {[%cal Ge7f6] Having better development and superior piece
activity, Black immediately opens the position.} 15. e4 ({After} 15. dxc5 Bf6
16. Qb1 {which was seen in the game½-½ (34) Bendig, F (2093)-Kent, D (1845)
IECG email 2000, Black's simplest follow-up would have been} Nc3 17. Qxb4 Nxe2+
18. Kh1 Bxa1 $19 {with a completely winning position.}) 15... Nb6 16. Nxb6 axb6
$19 {[%csl Ra6,Rf1] Black had a decisive advantage in the game 0-1 (23)
Kustanovich,M (2237)-Haslinger,S (2267) Witley 1999. It's impossible to avoid
