{[%evp 0,21,18,23,23,17,17,17,17,-20,1,1,11,11,11,-36,-29,-54,-34,-65,-43,-43,
-53,-45]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. a4 {
Besides preventing ...b7-b5, White is planning to seize even more queenside
space by means of a4-a5. On the downside, Black can now make use of the
vulnerable b4 and b3-squares.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6a5] A thematic reaction. Black's
positional threat is ...Na5. This is always a good concept when White has
weakened the b3-square by advancing the a-pawn.} 8. a5 {Practically forced.
Otherwise, Black will play ...Na5.} ({The alternatives are not challenging at
all. For example, the slow} 8. e3 {is well met by} Na5 {when it's not clear
how White is going to win the c4-pawn. At the same time, Black always has the
option of ...c7-c5.} 9. Nbd2 b6 {Even though there is nothing wrong with 9...
c5, this is the most ambitious continuation. Black is getting ready to defend
the c4-pawn by means of ...Ba6.} 10. Ne5 {This position occurred in the game
½-½ (43) Ereza Vizcarra,F (2107)-Buenafe Moya,J (2208) La Roda 2021. At this
point, very strong would have been} Ba6 $1 {This exchange sacrifice is very
typical for the Catalan. Accepting it is very dangerous.} 11. Nc6 {The idea is
to establish a blockade on the c6-square. Black, however, has enough resources
to neutralize this plan.} ({After} 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 {Black has tremendous
compensation due to the weak light squares in White's camp and the strong
c4-pawn which paralyzes White's development. Winning the pawn with} 12. Qc2 c5
13. Ndxc4 Nxc4 14. Nxc4 {allows} Qf3 $17 {with a fantastic attack on the light
squares. White is practically lost.}) 11... Nxc6 12. Bxc6 Rc8 13. Nf3 Qd6 14.
Ne5 {The point behind 11.Nc6. The easiest way to challenge White's
construction is} Nd5 {with the threat of ...f7-f6. After} 15. Bb5 Bb7 16. Nxc4
Qd8 $17 {[%csl Rb5,Rc4] White managed to win the pawn back but his pieces are
completely disorganized. Additionally, Black can make use of the extremely
weak light squares around the white king.}) ({A bit more logical is} 8. Na3 {
when Black will again settle for} Na5 {The possibility of ...Nb3 is always
very annoying for White.} 9. Qc2 ({As usual} 9. Bg5 $6 {is well met by} Nd5 10.
Bxe7 Qxe7 {After exchanging a pair of bishops, Black enjoys more space and
free piece play, The d8-square is available for the rook white the queen can
occupy a nice spot on b4. It's not clear how White will regain the pawn. After}
11. e4 Nb4 $17 {Black gains access to the d3-square as well. Attacking the
pawn with} 12. Qe2 $2 {does not work in view of} b6 $1 13. Rad1 ({Black is
winning an exchange after} 13. Nxc4 $2 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 Ba6 $19) 13... Ba6 $19 {
Black enjoyed a healthy extra pawn in the game 0-1 (29) Akopian, V (2678)
-Bologan,V (2652) Moscow 2002}) 9... Nb3 10. Rb1 Bd7 $1 {A very important
tempo, allowing Black to mobilize his queenside.} ({In the event of} 10... Nxd4
11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Nxc4 $44 {White enjoys a typical Catalan pressure. He has
enough compensation for the pawn.}) 11. Qxc4 Na5 $1 {One more precise move. It
turns out that there is no optimal retreat square for the white queen.} 12. Qc3
({After} 12. Qc2 $6 Bc6 $15 {[%cal Gc6e4] with the idea of ...Be4, White will
obviously regret playing moves like Na3 and Rb1.}) 12... Nd5 13. Qc2 Nb4 14.
Qd1 Bc6 {Black managed to activate his minor pieces by using the inferior
position of the white queen. This line is a clear illustration of the
drawbacks behind the advance a2-a4.} 15. Bd2 Be4 $11 {Black was in a full
control in the game 0-1 (16) Zaas,D (2305)-Gnilka,T (2325) ICCF email 2017})
8... Rb8 {Removing the rook from the opposition with the bishop and getting
ready to play ...b7-b5. White is pretty much forced to go for the following
sequence} 9. Qc2 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 ({Less precise is} 11. Be3 $6 {
when Black has the option of} Qg4 $1 12. h3 Qh5 13. Qxc4 Bd6 {It turns out
that White cannot restore the material balance since} 14. Bxa7 {is answered
with} Ra8 15. Be3 Rxa5 $17 {This position was reached in the game ½-½ (40)
Sisak,R (2205)-Lew,T (2201) ICCF email 2017. Black is a healthy pawn up.})
11... Qc5 12. Be3 Qb4 13. Ra4 Qb3 14. Rxc4 Qxc2 15. Rxc2 Bd6 16. Bxa7 {In my
opinion, this is White's best continuation.} ({A top-level game saw} 16. Na3 {
which does not manage to pose problems. Black went for the precise} Bd7 {
[%cal Gd7a4] winning an important tempo in view of the threat of ...Ba4.} 17.
Rcc1 $6 {This is already an inaccuracy.} ({Better would have been} 17. Ra1 {
with approximate equality.}) 17... b6 18. axb6 axb6 19. Nc4 Ba4 20. Rd2 Bb4 21.
Rd3 {This position occurred in the game ½-½ (24) Caruana, F (2822)
-Dominguez Perez,L (2739) Saint Louis 2018. At this point, Black could have
played} Rfd8 22. Ne5 Bd6 $17 {when White has no compensation for the pawn.})
16... Ra8 {This move practically forces a draw -} 17. Bc5 Rxa5 18. Bxd6 cxd6
19. Rxd6 Ra1 20. Rd1 Bd7 21. Rc7 Rb8 {The equality is obvious, as illustrated
by the following lines.} 22. Nc3 ({After} 22. Rxb7 Rxb7 23. Bxb7 Ra2 $11 {
Black quickly regains the pawn.}) ({White can even go wrong by playing} 22.
Bxb7 $2 {when after} Ba4 {[%cal Gf6e8] Black is almost winning in view of ...
Ne8 on the next move. White is forced to accept the position arising after} 23.
b3 Bxb3 24. Rf1 Ra7 25. Rc8+ Rxc8 26. Bxc8 Bc4 $17 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gc4e2,
Ga7c7] Black has two threats - ...Be2 and ...Rc7. White needs to sacrifice a
pawn in order to save the bishop.}) 22... Rxd1+ 23. Nxd1 Rc8 24. Rxc8+ Bxc8 $11
{The draw is obvious.} *

