1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nc3 {This line is very
popular nowadays. You can see a number of top-level games in this direction.
By temporarily sacrificing a pawn, White is playing for quick development and
good central control. In the main lines, White is trying to get a risk-free
position with hopes for a tiny edge. For a long period of time, this system
was a bit annoying for Black. Fortunately, powerful engines indicated how
Black can obtain complete equality. I suggest the principled line} dxc4 7. Ne5
Nc6 {A thematic reaction to Ne5 in Catalan positions. Black immediately uses
the vulnerability of the d4-pawn. White's only try for an advantage is
connected with} 8. Bxc6 ({The structure arising after} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 {is
completely harmless for Black. In return for the vulnerable c4-pawn, Black
enjoys a nice pressure on the b-file. Additionally, the defence of the d4-pawn
is always an issue for White.} 9. Bxc6 {The most principled continuation.} ({
After} 9. O-O Rb8 {Black is ready to follow with the thematic ...c6-c5. White
can find himself in trouble if he refuses to grab the c6-pawn. The following
examples are quite illustrative.} 10. Qc2 $6 {This position was reached in the
game 0-1 (33) Moskalenko,A (2490)-Popov,I (2596) Sochi 2016} ({Another
possible direction is} 10. Qa4 $6 Qxd4 11. Be3 Qe5 12. Qxa7 {This position
occurred in 0-1 (45) Maltsevskaya,A (2327)-Bocharov,I (2568) Moscow 2021. Now,
Black's most precise reaction would have been} Rb7 13. Qd4 Qxd4 14. Bxd4 Rd8
15. e3 Nd5 $17 {When looking at this position, we can conclude that Black's
tripled pawns are not that bad. Besides having an extra pawn, Black puts a
very annoying pressure along the b-file. The immediate threat is ...c6-c5.})
10... Qxd4 11. Be3 Qe5 12. Bxc6 Bb7 $17 {After the exchange of the
light-squared bishops, Black is better. Due to the pressure along the b-file,
White cannot easily win the c4-pawn back.}) 9... Rb8 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bxb7 ({
Sacrificing the d4-pawn with} 11. Qa4 {only creates problems for White -} Qxd4
12. Be3 Bxc6 13. Qxc6 Qd6 14. Qxc4 Rb4 $15 {Black was slightly better in the
game ½-½ (49) Shipov, S (2625)-Lautier, J (2653) Moscow 2001. White still
needs to demonstrate the way to equality since the b2-pawn is doomed.}) 11...
Rxb7 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black is doing completely fine. A thematic idea in this
structure would be ...c7-c5. After the exchange of the central pawns, the
vulnerable c4-pawn is balanced by Black's pressure along the b-file.}) 8...
bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 Nd5 $1 {I consider this rare move to
be the ultimate solution to Black's problems in this line. This judgement is
strongly supported by powerful engines. In the arising position with
opposite-coloured bishops, Black enjoys decent compensation for the pawn.} ({
The main line goes} 11... c5 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Be3 Qc7 14. O-O-O {[%cal Ge3d4,
Gf2f3] After putting his bishop on d4, White can start preparing the advance
of his kingside pawns. The right way to do so would be f2-f3 followed by g2-g4,
and h2-h4. We know that in positions with opposite-coloured bishops, the
possibility of building an attack is what matters. Additionally, the exchange
of the queens is also favourable for White due to Black's weakened queenside
structure. That being said, the position remains objectively equal. I just
don't like giving White good practical chances.}) 12. Qxc4 a5 {This is the
point. Now, Black is ready to follow with ...Ba6. White's best move is} 13. Bd2
{Overprotecting the c3-knight and getting ready to answer ...Ba6 with Qc5.} ({
In case of} 13. O-O Ba6 14. Qa4 Rfd8 {Having a lead in development, Black will
easily win the pawn back. The natural} 15. Re1 {is well met by} Qb4 $1 {
when after} 16. a3 Nxc3 17. axb4 Nxa4 18. Rxa4 Rxd4 19. Rxa5 Rxb4 $11 {The
position was completely equal in the game ½-½ (32) Bindrich, F (2599)
-Nisipeanu,L (2667) Magdeburg 2019}) ({Playing} 13. f3 {without Bd2 does not
give White any advantage -} Ba6 14. Qc5 {This position occurred in the game
½-½ (30) Musyuk,L (2350)-Souhardo,B (2382) Budapest 2021. Since the white
bishop is not on d2, Black can play} Qxc5 15. dxc5 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Rab8 $44 {
with enough compensation for the pawn. White cannot develop his light-squared
bishop in view of ...Rb2. At the same time, Black is ready to proceed with ...
Rfd8 followed by ...Rd5.}) ({The attempt to keep everything protected with} 13.
Qa4 Ba6 14. Qc2 {was seen in the game ½-½ (71) Jogstad,M (2334)-Kenneskog,T 
(2278) Uppsala 2021. Unfortunately for White, however, this approach is too
slow. Black's most principled reaction is to open the position with} c5 {
Fighting for the initiative without paying too much attention to the material
is the most typical way of handling middlegames with opposite-coloured bishops.
} 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Be3 ({In the event of} 16. dxc5 d4 17. O-O Rfc8 18. c6 Bb5
$36 {Black will regain one of the sacrificed pawns, keeping a dangerous
initiative. The light squares around the white king are way too vulnerable.})
16... cxd4 17. Bxd4 Rfe8 {White has nothing better than giving the pawn back
by playing} 18. O-O Qxe2 19. Qxe2 Bxe2 20. Rfe1 a4 $11 {with equality.}) ({
Taking on d5 with} 13. Nxd5 $6 {is not a good option since Black immediately
starts putting pressure along the e-file.} exd5 14. Qc2 ({Taking a second pawn
with} 14. Qxd5 $6 {is very risky. Black's most precise continuation would be}
Re8 15. O-O ({The attempt to keep the extra material with} 15. Be3 $2 {gives
Black a winning position. The following sequence is pretty much forced} Qb4+
16. Bd2 Bb7 17. Qf5 Qxd4 18. Bc3 {White is playing strictly only moves in
order to avoid the immediate defeat. Now, Black has the powerful} Rxe2+ $1 19.
Kxe2 Re8+ {with a winning attack. You need to carefully study this line, since
Black has to make a series of only moves in order to win.} 20. Kf1 Qc4+ 21. Kg1
Qc6 22. f3 Qb6+ 23. Kg2 ({After} 23. Kf1 Ba6+ 24. Kg2 Re2+ 25. Kh3 Qh6+ 26. Kg4
Re6 27. h4 Bc8 {we have a transposition to 23.Kg2.}) 23... Re2+ 24. Kh3 Qh6+
25. Kg4 Re6 $1 26. h4 Bc8 27. Kh3 Re8 28. Qxc8 Rxc8 $19 {Even though White can
still put up some resistance, Black is objectively winning.}) 15... Qxe2 16.
Be3 Be6 $40 {The weakness of the light squares around the white king gives
Black more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Re8 15. Be3 Qb4+ 16.
Qd2 Qe7 $11 {In my opinion, White has nothing better than repeating the
position. The problem is that after} 17. O-O $2 Bh3 $19 {[%cal Ge7e4] Black is
winning in view of the threat ...Qe4.}) ({A recent high-level game saw} 13. Be3
{1/2-1/2 (62) Cheparinov, I (2664)-Giri, A (2772) Warsaw 2021 At this point,
Black should have played} Ba6 {when after} 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Qc2 {the most
precise is to seize even more queenside space with} a4 {A possible follow-up
would be} 16. O-O Rfe8 17. Rfe1 h5 {[%cal Ge7d7,Gh5h4] Black is ready to
proceed with ... Qd7 followed by ...h5-h4 building a kingside initiative.
White's extra pawn is not relevant.}) 13... Ba6 14. Qc5 Qd7 15. f3 {A
generally useful move in this pawn structure. White is making the f2-square
available for the king.} ({The natural} 15. Rc1 {also requires some precision
from Black. The best move seems to be} Rfb8 {Provoking b2-b3 is useful in this
structure. In the future, Black will use the b3-pawn as a hook for the advance
...a5-a4.} 16. b3 ({After} 16. Nd1 {a thematic idea is} Re8 {[%cal Ge6e5]
preparing ...e6-e5. White has nothing better than} 17. Nc3 Reb8 $11 {with a
repetition.}) 16... Nxc3 17. Rxc3 ({The alternative} 17. Qxc3 {is even worse
since Black can play ...Qb5 in a favourable moment.} a4 18. f3 axb3 19. axb3
Qb5 20. Qe3 Qxb3 21. Qxb3 ({In case of} 21. Kf2 Qxe3+ 22. Kxe3 Rb3+ 23. Kf2 Rb2
$11 {[%cal Ga6b5,Ga8a2] Black's activity is more than enough for equality.})
21... Rxb3 22. Rxc7 Rb2 $44 {Once again, White has no winning chances due to
Black's tremendous activity.}) 17... Rb5 18. Qxc7 Qxd4 19. Be3 {This position
was reached in the game 1-0 (51) Oparin,G (2613)-Buhmann,R (2568) Skopje 2019.
Now, Black should have played} Qf6 $1 {keeping an eye on the c3-rook. A
possible follow-up would be} 20. Rc1 Rbb8 21. f3 a4 $44 {with sufficient
compensation for the pawn.}) ({A blunder is} 15. O-O-O $2 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Bxe2
$19 {when Black had a winning advantage in the game 0-1 (60) Ning, K (2327)
-Xiao, Y (2301) Xinghua 2020. The white king is way too vulnerable.}) 15...
Rfb8 16. Rb1 {White tries to avoid b2-b3.} ({The problem is that after} 16. b3
{which was seen in the game 1-0 (53) Zanan, E (2535)-Salimova, N (2395)
Belgrade 2021, Black has} Rb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6c6] with the idea of ...Rc6. The
unstable c3-knight does not allow White to fight for an advantage.} 17. Rc1 ({
After} 17. Kf2 {Black can force a draw by means of} Rc6 18. Qxa5 Bb7 19. Qb5
Ba6 $11) 17... Rc6 18. Qa3 Nb4 19. Kf2 Qxd4+ 20. Be3 Qe5 $132 {Black enjoys a
huge activity. Practically speaking, his position is easier to handle.}) 16...
Rb6 $1 {Once again, we see this typical motif. The next move is ...Rc6.} 17.
Kf2 {The most natural continuation.} ({In case of} 17. Qxa5 {Black has the
beautiful} Qd8 $1 {[%cal Ga6e2] safeguarding the a8-rook and threatening ...
Bxe2. One of the subtle points is that} 18. Qc5 {will be met by} Qe8 $1 {
[%csl Re2][%cal Ge8e2,Ga6e2,Gb6c6] Besides taking prophylactic measure against
Nxd5, Black prepares ...Rc6. White should really do something about the
restricted position of his queen.} 19. a4 {The idea of this move is to secure
the a3-square for the queen.} ({Another direction is} 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. O-O Rc6
21. Qxd5 Rc2 22. Qg5 ({After} 22. Bf4 Rxe2 23. Rbc1 Rb8 24. b3 Rxa2 $11 {
the position is equal.}) 22... Qxe2 23. Rf2 Qd3 24. Rc1 Rxb2 $44 {Black is out
of risk due to the activity of his pieces.}) {On the downside, the move a2-a4
weakens the b-file. Therefore, the logical follow-up will be} 19... Rab8 20.
O-O Rxb2 21. Rxb2 Rxb2 22. Qa5 Qc6 23. Nxd5 exd5 24. Rc1 Bc4 $44 {with a
decent compensation for the pawn.}) 17... Rc6 18. Qa3 Rc4 ({Another option is} 
18... Nb6 $5 19. Be3 Nc4 $44 {when Black enjoyed good compensation in the game
0-1 (35) Goryachkina,A (2592) -Dubov,D (2699) Sochi 2020}) 19. Rhd1 Rxd4 20.
Be3 Nxe3 21. Kxe3 e5 22. Kf2 ({But not} 22. Qxa5 $2 Qc6 $1 23. Kf2 Bxe2 $19 {
when Black is winning.}) 22... Qc6 $132 {Black's more active pieces neutralize
White's slightly favourable pawn structure. The position is balanced.} *

