{[%evp 0,30,18,24,24,17,17,17,17,-11,1,1,11,9,14,-11,-25,-28,-4,-12,25,-2,9,-6,
7,2,3,-7,-7,-13,3,-36,-58]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O
6. Nc3 dxc4 7. O-O {This gambit variation shouldn't be underestimated. In the
long-term, White is planning to build a strong centre with e2-e4. On the other
hand, as it very often happens in the Catalan, the c4-pawn shouldn't be
underestimated. With a knight on c3, it's even more difficult to regain the
missing pawn. Black's most logical reply is} Nc6 {Besides putting pressure on
d4, Black is ready to protect the c4-pawn by means of ...Na5. Later on, he can
follow with ...c7-c5.} 8. e3 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gf1d1] White is planning to
gradually build his central strategy. If allowed, he will proceed with Qe2
followed by Rd1. If Black loses the c4-pawn without getting something in
return, his position will be worse.} ({Getting rid of the dark-squared bishop
with} 8. Bg5 {always comes into consideration in the Catalan. The drawback is
that having less space, Black welcomes exchanges of the minor pieces.} Nd5 9.
Bxe7 {This position was reached in the game 0-1 (57) Fressinet, L (2633)
-Firouzja,A (2702) chess24.com INT 2020} ({After} 9. Bd2 {Another decent
option is} Nb6 $15 {White has no compensation for the missing pawn.}) {At this
point, Black should have played} 9... Qxe7 {[%cal Gd5b6,Gf8d8] keeping the
d8-square available for the rook. The next moves will be ...Nb6, ...Rd8, and
eventually ...e6-e5.} 10. e3 Nb6 11. Nd2 ({A typical answer to} 11. Qe2 $6 {is}
e5 {when after} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5 $17 {Black enjoys a healthy extra
pawn.}) 11... Rd8 {[%cal Ge6e5] Remember this thematic setup. Everything is
ready for ...e6-e5.} 12. Qe2 ({The inclusion of the moves} 12. a4 a5 {would
only favour Black since the b4-square becomes available for the knight. The
most logical follow-up would be} 13. Qe2 e5 14. Nxc4 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 exd4 16.
exd4 Qb4 17. Qxb4 Nxb4 18. d5 Bf5 $15 {Black has the advantage due to the
superior activity of his minor pieces and White's vulnerable structure.}) 12...
e5 13. Nxc4 exd4 14. Nxb6 cxb6 15. exd4 Qxe2 16. Nxe2 Bg4 $15 {Black has the
initiative.}) ({The ambitious} 8. e4 {is always a valid option. The main
problem of the early e2-e4 is the pressure on d4. Now, the white queen cannot
easily leave the d1-square. Therefore, White usually tries to put his pawn on
e4 after having put his rook to d1. Another drawback of the advance e2-e4 is
that now there is no pressure along the diagonal h1-a8. Black's most natural
reaction is} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] immediately preparing ...b7-b5. Even though
White has a wide range of options in this position, he is mainly fighting for
equality.} 9. a4 {Preventing ...b7-b5 but weakening the squares b4 and
especially b3.} ({An old game saw} 9. Re1 $6 b5 {This game of Geller is a good
illustration of what happens when White is playing on general grounds.} 10. e5
Nd5 11. Ne4 Ncb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3] A typical resource. The knight is heading
for d3. We can now see the importance of the c4-pawn. White is planning to
bring his queen to the kingside. Such kind of attacks, however, wouldn't work
when Black has good centralization.} 12. Nfg5 {[%cal Gd1h5]} h6 13. Nh3 Nd3 $19
{Black's advantage is already decisive. Kavalek tried} 14. Bxh6 {mostly out of
desperation. After} gxh6 15. Qg4+ Kh7 16. f4 f5 $19 {White could have
immediately resigned. 0-1 (24) Kavalek,L (2545)-Geller,E (2590) Wijk aan Zee
1977}) ({Dubious is} 9. a3 $6 {[%csl Rb3] White prevents ...Nb4 but weakens
the b3-square. Black's typical reaction is} Na5 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga5b3] with the
idea to follow with ...b7-b5 and ...Nb3.} 10. Bf4 {This position was reached
in the game 1-0 (29) Salem, A (2638)-Hess, R (2568) Chess.com INT 2017 At this
point, Black could have played} Nb3 11. Rb1 b5 12. Qe2 a6 $17 {[%cal Gf8e8,
Gc8b7] Black has an obvious advantage. White does not have compensation for
the missing pawn. In order to prepare for all possible central breaks, Black
will play ...Bb7 and ...Re8. In the long run, the advance ...c7-c5 will be
executed.}) ({Playing for initiative with} 9. Qa4 $6 {[%cal Gf1d1] does not
work quite well. Black should take the pawn immediately} Nxd4 {Otherwise,
White would play Rd1 with a huge positional advantage.} 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Be3 {
This position was reached in the game 0-1 (31) Birnbaum, W (2016)-Stern, R  
(2517) Rostock 2012 Now, Black could have played} b5 $1 {A very strong
intermediate move. Black has a big advantage in all the lines.} 12. Qa5 ({After
} 12. Nxb5 $2 Qd7 13. Nc3 Qxa4 14. Nxa4 Bd7 15. Nc5 Bc6 $19 {[%csl Rb2,Re4]
[%cal Gb8b5] White's position is collapsing since besides the extra pawn,
Black has different threats such as ...Rxb2 and ...Rb5.}) ({The tactical idea} 
12. Qxb5 Rxb5 13. Bxd4 Rxb2 14. Nd5 {is not threatening since after} exd5 15.
Bxb2 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 dxe4 $17 {Black has big material advantage.}) 12... Qe5 13.
a4 a6 14. axb5 axb5 $17 {Black managed to stabilize the position and will keep
at least one of the two extra pawns. His advantage is close to decisive.}) ({
Protecting the d4-pawn with} 9. Be3 {gives Black time to play} b5 {[%csl Re4]
[%cal Gb5b4] when White should already reckon with the vulnerability of the
e4-pawn. The threat is ...b5-b4.} 10. a3 {Despite preventing ...b5-b4, this
move is not good in principle due to the weakness of the b3-square.} ({The
position arising after} 10. d5 exd5 11. exd5 Na5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb5b4] is
favourable for Black. In this structure, the d5-pawn is typically quite
vulnerable. Black's next move is ...b5-b4.} 12. Ne5 ({The alternative} 12. Bxa7
{does not manage to solve White's problems. After} Rb7 13. Qd4 {Black manages
to capture the central pawn by means of} b4 14. Na4 Qxd5 {A possible follow-up
will be} 15. Bc5 Bxc5 16. Nxc5 Rb5 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 $17 {when Black has a stable
position and healthy extra pawn.}) 12... b4 13. Ne2 Bd6 $17 {This position
occurred in the game 0-1 (54) Klewe,W (2191)-Kuitert,C (2102) ICCF email 2017.
White does not have any compensation for the pawn.}) 10... Na5 {Once again, we
see this thematic reaction} 11. Qc2 {This position was reached in the game
½-½ (47) Filippov,V (2455)-Kiriakov,P (2480) Moscow 1995. Now, the critical
would have been} Nb3 12. Rad1 a6 {[%cal Gc8b7] Positionally speaking, this is
the most sensible move. Now, however, Black should reckon with the advance
d4-d5.} ({A decent alternative is} 12... c6 $5 13. h4 a6 {For the time being,
Black keeps his bishop on c8.} ({The reason is that after} 13... Bb7 14. e5 Nd5
